{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866421/1930070101/0004.xml":{"full_text":"FOUR\ni he Douglas Daily Dispatch\nPIONEER DAILY PAPER OF DOUGLAS\nPublished By The\nDISPATCH PUBLISHING COMPANY\nJAMES LOGIE, President and General Manager\nALBERT M. SAMES G. M. LOGIE\nVice President Secretary and Treasurer\nJOHN A. CURRY, City~Editor\nL. R. HANCOCK, Advertising Manager\nPcbNshed Every Morning Except Monday\nDispatch Bldg, 528-530 Eleventh BL Phones Sl-82\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nEntered at the Postoffice at Douglas. Arizona, as sec\nond-class mail matter. The Associated Press is ex\nclusively entitled t\" the use for re-publication of all\nn<-wa credited to k or not otherwise credited in this\npaper and also the local news published here. All\nrlvhu of re-publication of special dispatches are also\nn served\nSUBSCRIPnON RATES:\nOne Year\nBit Months 400\nOne Month '75\nSingle Copy Z 05\nBy Mail or Carrier, Payable In Advance\nSubscribers who fail to receive their paper regularly\nare requested to notify Lie business office promptly,\npreferably before 9 o'clock in the morning n the day\npaper is missed.\nRrpresented Nat\u2019anallv By\nM C. MOGENSEN COMPANY. Inc.\nLa* Angeles San Francisco Seattle\n433 So. Spring 564 8t 603 Stewart St.\nPortland 350 N. Mich. Ave. Detroit\nBroadway N. Y. 122 E. 42nd 3044 W Grand Bid\nCopies of The Dispatch may be secured at any of these\noffices, where full data regarding the Douglas market\nmay also be had.\nA COMPLETE AND MODERN JOB DEPARTMENT\n|Some \u201cGo Get \u2019Em\u201d Needed]\nSome idea of what may be accomplished in the\nway of creating a market for a commodity where\nno market has existed theretofore is given in a\nreport emanating from China to the effect that the\n100 per cent American delicacy, ice cream, is rapidly\nbecoming an important import from the United\nStates.\nNot until 1925 was ice cream introduced to the\nChinese and then only when an American medicine\nman and amateur author opened an ice cream\nparlorin the heart of Shanghai, catering chiefly to\nforeigners. Soon the Chinese became patrons and\nword passed along as to the merits of the strange\ndish which the foreign devils had brought from their\nhome across the sea. So great became the demand\nfor the delicacy that other restaurants and confec\ntioners were compelled to stock their establishments\nand eventually installed their own manufacturing\nmachinery.\nToday every ship from Seattle or San Francisco\nbrings its cargo of ice cream and the aggregate\nshipments amount to an enormous monetary figure\neach month. Not alone do their dairy interests\nprofit, but the machinery manufacturers as well for\nvirtually every Chinese community is installing ice\nplants to accommodate the demand for the Ameri\ncan luxury.\nAmerican enterprise, however, appears to lag in\nthe Orient as a general rule. Even in the Philip\npines, Spanish and English firms have obtained a\nfoothold which in future years will no doubt \u2018\u2018freeze\nout\u201d the United States industries in the islands,\nespecially in the event the island people are granted\nindependence by Uncle Sam. It would seem that\nhere is afforded a wonderful opportunity for the\ngovernment to alleviate the unemployment situation\nand over-production on the farms but appropriating\na fund to be used exclusively in promoting a demand\nfor American products in the Orient. Even a sub\nsidy such as is granted steamship lines would accom\nplish wonders in this great and growing market to\nthe west.\nDistinctive Individuality\nForeigners and American malcontents who com\nplain that the people of the United States are\nbecoming standardized may gain some degree of hope\nin the suggestion broached in high government circles\nwhich would involve the finger-printing of all per\nsons in the country.\nThe idea, while revolutionary and drastic, would,\nif adopted, at least give every American that indi\nviduality which the Europeans and a certain portion\nof home-grown intelligencia declare he lacks. For\nscientists tell us that no two finger-prints are\nexactly alike and may easily be distinguished under\nthe Bertillion lens.\nThe proposal originally was aimed in the general\ndirection of organized crime, whatever that means.\nBut as administration heads contemplated the scope\nof the innovation, it became obvious that universal\nfinger-printing would entail other and greater possi\nbilities. Fraud, forgery, false claims to parentage\nwhich blood tests fail to explode, and a thousand\nother uses comes to mind.\nIn China a uniform system of finger-printing\nhas been urged by the minister of the interior.\nHitherto police of each large Chinese city has had\ntheir own system of applying the system and the\nresult has been poor. In the United States, officials\nof the department of justice are reported to be in\nunanimous support of the proposal and favor, com\npulsory finger-printing of babies at birth and by\ncity or county officers charged with the anission.\nOf course, there will be a protest if the idea\ngains ground, but it must be said for the proposal\nthat it would doubtless go far towards thwarting\ncrime and would tighten the present lax methods\nby which wanted criminals are permitted to wander\nover the country.\nAn Eye For An Eye j\n4.\nAs was anticipated. England has taken steps to\nretaliate against the new American tariff measure\nby prohibiting importation into the United Kingdom\nof certain American products. Just now the reprisal\nis confined to importation of certain grades of\nAmerican apples and the barrier is to be in effect\nfrom July 7 to Nov. 15.\nBut the administration at Washington is said to\nbe unperturbed by this retaliatory action by Mother\nEngland. The action is taken for the most part as\na gesture by which the British government may at\nonce express the chagrin of the country over the\nAmerican tariff and sooth the ruffled constituency\nagainst the next election. I\nThere is another feature to England\u2019s closed\ndoor to our products. Not to be outdone, the United\nStates might go a step further and bar the ports\nto that perennial English invasion of lecturers who\nannually flock to our .shores to set us right as to\nwhat is wrong with the world\u2014our own world, par\nticularly. Then the blissfully unconscious yokelry of\nthe United States could go right on believing the\nlittle old United States is the best country in the\nworld despite all its faults and the bitterness of the\nannual British disillusionment would be spared us.\nNow. there\u2019s a tip for the administration, f. o. b.\nDouglas.\nWith Other Editors\nPOINTS TO MOTIVE IN LINGLE CASE\n(Arizona Republican)\nThere was something more than humor in the\nstatement of Will Rogers yesterday regarding gang- J\nster killings in Chicago, his declaration that no\ninnocent person had been killed by a gangster in\nChicago since 1892, and that gangsters were not\nkilled by members of rival gangs, but that death\nwas the penalty for double-crossing. This latter\nstatement is not quite in accord with the known i\nrecord as to reprisals between rival gangs. But\ngenerally \"double-crossing\u201d is a capital offense for\nwhich death is meted out.\nMr. Rogers\u2019 remarks were no doubt inspired by\nthe disclosures on Thursday of the banking opera\ntions of Alfred Lingle, the murdered Chicago re\nporter. and his weekly deposits in cash in one bank,\nsometimes running as high as SI,OOO.\nThis income was aside from his modest salary\nas a reporter which came to him in check and did\nnot figure in the cash deposits. A discovery of the\nsource of this cash income, it is thought, would go\nsome w\u2019ay tow\u2019ard furnishing a motive for his\nslaying. v\nThere were two items in the news of the killing\nmore than two weeks ago that seemed to point to\na possible motive. One was the friendliness of\nLingle and Al Capone. The other, which particu\nlarly arrested the attention of reporters, was the\nstatement that Lingle owned a $25,000 country house\nat a fashionable lake resort and an apartment in\nChicago. Both these possessions would connote some\nconsiderable wealth behind them to maintain them.\nNobody at all familiar with the story of racket\neering. especially in Chicago, gave any heed to the\nsuggestion that Lingle had been killed because of j\nany news he had printed about rackets, or to pre\nvent him from making disclosures. Though as a\nveteran police reporter he probably knew much of\nthe underworld against which the paper for which\nhe worked was carrying on a vigorous campaign.\nThe Tribune, however, did not base its attack upon\ngangs and racketeering on exclusive information, but\nupon stories which were common to all the Chicago\nnewspapers.\nNor, have gangsters seemed to care what the\nnewspapers printed about them. The heated imagi\nnation of the wildest-eyed reporter could not have\nconjured up anything worse than the papers had\nprinted again and again and never had any publica\ntion awakened the active resentment of a gangster.\nIn the penal code of gangland there seem to be\nonly two offenses defined, and both are capital.\nOne is the double-cross, or the disloyalty of a mem\nber to the gang. The other is the intrusion of a\nrival gang upon territory within which another gang\nclaims dominion. The latter produces internecine\nwar and the former, assassination. Every known\nvictim is supposed to have violated one or the other\nof these articles of the code.\nSHOULD WORK BOTH WAYS\n(Coconino Sun)\nMaricopa county\u2019s claim for more of the gas tax\nmoney because more is paid in from that county is\nnot consistent with -their attitude as to the state\nschool tax division. In the latter case other counties\nof the state are helping to pay Maricopa\u2019s school\nbill because that county has more children than\nmany of the other counties. It\u2019s a poor rule that\ndoes not work both ways.\nMore Truth Than Poetry i\nBy JAMES J. MONTAGUE I\n\u201cHOW HAPPY I\u2019D BE WITH EITHER\u201d\nI like to climb aboard my car,\nWhich stands by' my abode.\nAnd drive it daily fast and far\nAlong some country road.\nTo turn and twist that way and this,\nUrged on by super-power,\nBut if I do I\u2019ll have to miss\nThe No Grit toothpaste hour.\nI like to turn the little knob\nWith an attentive hand\nUntil I catch the beat and throb\nOf Benny Bilkins\u2019 band.\nBut when upon these strains I feed.\nMy peace of mind is marred\nFor then, of course I cannot speed\nAlong the boulevard.\nAboard my little bus I climb,\nThe countryside to roam,\nBut in a fleeting space of time\nThe radio calls me home.\nI listen to some vocal star\nA little while, and then\nI have to switch her off\u2014the car\nHas called me out again.\nIf I possessed a car alone\nOr just a radio set,\nI would not daily need to moan\nAnd fume and fuss and fret\nWith either one of them to part\nI am extremely loath,\nAnd yet it daily breaks my heart\nTo get along with both.\nTHE LAND OF OPPORTUNITY\nAll caddies hope to be professionals, and by the\ntime they grow up there will be enough new golf\ncourses to provide jobs for all of them.\nCONSISTENT\nWe heard the other day about an investor who\nnever bought any stock on a margin unless it was\nstock in a marginal railroad.\nWORTH BEHOLDING\nWhat we'd like to see is a literary Boston boot\nlegger unloading a truck of forbidden books in a\nread-easy.\nALL SETTLED\nJ Well, anyway, a German instead 01 a Litnu\n-1 anian is the American heavyweight prize fight\n^qjiamp.\n(Copyright, 1930, by Bell Syndicate, Inc.)\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH, TUESDAY MORNING, JULY 1, 1930.\nI W wi\naV J HH >^3\nA\nJ-\n*ap 7\nAs/ r\nJ fl H -A\nJ\nxi\n\u2014'2^^^ ^s\u2014\nA New Yorker\nAt Large\n\nBy MARK BARRON\nNEW YORK\u2014The gay White\nWay, once the dazzling candle that\nlured so many out-of-towners to\nNew York, is becoming dimmer.\nEspecially since prohibition have\ni the bright lights been flickering\ninto darkness.\nLuxurious cabarets and lobster\npalaces\u2014such as Churchill\u2019s, the\nPalais Royale, Shanley\u2019s, the Clar\nidge Grill, Rector\u2019s and Bustonoby's\n\u2014have departed with the cham\npagne era.\nIn their places came dark end\nsecluded places of amusement,\nknown only to those who knew\ntheir way around. Visitors from\nother cities found themselves rele\ngated to a new type of cabaret\nfounded by the very smart Chinese.\nThese wise Orientals bought the\nold lobster palaces, installed chop\nsuey as the main item on the\nmenu, entertained with a dance\norchestra and a tabloid show. And\nthey removed the irritable cover\ncharge.\n\nBig Profits\nThe Chinese syndicate which op\n-1 erates a chain of these chow mein\nparlors have netted something like\n$5,090,000 profit in the last seven\nyears.\nAmerican restaurant owners con\nsidered this huge profit and began\nto adopt some of the Chinese cus\ntoms. The first of these Occi\ndental palaces to combat the Chi\nnese monopoly presents a show\nwith 50 people and asks no cover\ncharge. In the past 36 weeks it\nhas netted a half million dollars in\nprofit.\nNow, in a suburb near Manhat\ntan, they have introduced an out\ndoor cabaret. It seats 3.500 people\nand offers a show of 50 dancers\nand two orchestras. The prices are\ncomparatively low.\nYes, the gay White Way is not\n\nw\nMother Nature\u2019s Curio Shop\n4\n1 lair J\nA ROSSIAM PLANT WHICH CURLS DOWN\nAND PULLS ITSELF UP ST THE ROOTS*\nAND THEN GOES ROLLING ALONG\nIN THE WIND, SCATTERING (TS SEED.\nr\nSICKLE-BILLED\nHUMMINGBIRDS FEED\nON NECTAR. FROM. LONG-TUBED,\nCURVED FLOWERS', AND THEV HAVE \"\"\u2014A\nBILLS SUITABLE FOR- THE TASK. _\nOLLJ *OIO3O BY NEA SERVICE, INC.\nSky Writing\nAunt Het\nBv ROBERT QUILLEN\nX\u00a5\u00a5\nI\nI Ho\nI I\nI RmO:' i\n\u201cAmy wouldn't o\u2019 hurt my\nfcelin\u2019s by not invitin\u2019 me to\nhe.r party if she hadn't thought\nme sap enough to swallow her\nlyin \u2019excuses.\u201d\nso brilliant as it was once. Huw\ni ever, prices have been lowered with\nthe lights, for visitors are becom\ning smart. No longer can the city\nslicker sell them a gold brick or\nthe Brooklyn bridge. They are de\nmanding and getting their money\u2019s\nworth.\nNo Chance\nSandy: \u201cSay, Mon, when is\nAnnie McTavish goin\u2019 to let you\nmarry her?\u201d\nAndy: \u201cIt\u2019s very uncertain, Mon.\nSome fool gave her a big box of\nletter paper with her name printed\non it. She won\u2019t get married till\nit\u2019s used up\u2014an\u2019 she writes very\nfew letters on account of the post\nage.\u201d\u2014Keolite News.\nSuccess: Quitting the farm to\nbecome a banker to get rich\nenough to retire and live on a\nfarm.\u2014Quillen.\nWashington Letter\nBy RODNEY DUTCHER\nNEA Service Writer\n\nWASHINGTON.\u2014Primary results\nare used to prove almost anything.\nThe political lessons which various\nfactions and individual analysts\nhave drawn from the dozen or\nmore primary elections this year\nhave often been contradictory and\nin most such explanations of the\nresults one man\u2019s guess as to the\nsignificance of the result has been\nas good as another\u2019s.\nLooking at all the results at\nonce it can be said that the gen\neral thing thus far proved is that\nthe big political machines are as\nstrong as ever, that organization\nsupport is still the most important\nfactor in politics and that the va\nrious states still seem \u201csot\u201d in\ntheir political ways. It is possible\nto draw the inference that the\nvoters are not thoroughly satisfied\nwith the controlling set-up in\nWashington, but a conclusive dem\nonstration of that theory will have\nto wait for the congressional elec\ntion of November.\nDwight Morrow's smashing vic\ntory in New Jersey may be reason\nably attributed to the facts that\nNew Jersey is still very wet, that\nthe G. O. P. organization which\nsupported him is still very strong\nand that Morrow has built up great\npersonal prestige. He might have\nwon without any of the three fac\ntors, but each contributed impor\ntantly to his big majority.\nMorrow was much the biggest\nman in the senatorial primary. The\nsize of his majority indicates his\nelection in November. He had all\nthe republican organization in the\nstare, apparently, for although the\nEssex county G. O. P. was formally\nsupporting Frelinghuysen the fact\nthat Morrow won by four to one\nin that section indicates that the\nsupport was unenthusiastic, if it\nexisted.\n\nInsurgeri's Win in West\nObviously, few Jersey republicans\nwere sufficiently worried about J\nPresident Hoover\u2019s renomination\nproblem to desire to spare him the\nanxiety created by Morrow as the\none man talked of to oppose Hoov\ner in 1932. Many voted for Mor\nrow with the idea that they were\ngiving him a boost toward the\npresidency.\nSenator Schalls renomination in\nMinnesota was an endorsement of\nthe western republican insurgents,\nwhereas the nomination of Gover\nnor Christianson, his opponent and j\na close friend of White House Sec- 1\nretaries Akerson and Newton, would\nhave been taken as an important j\nvictory for the administration. I\nThere haven't, however, been any!\ndecisive administration defeats or\nvictories in the primaries to date.\nThe White House keeps out of\nthese fights and so avoids grief.\nCongressman White\u2019s defeat of\nformer Governor Brewster for the\nMaine senatorial nomination was\nexpected. White had the backing\nof the conservative state machine. I\nwhich always wins with the aid of\npublic utilities and other corpora\ntions. Brewster only had personal\npopularity and a good record as\ngovernor.\nSenator Simmons of North Caro\nlina would not have been licked by\nJosiah Bailey in the democratic\nprimary if he had not alienated\nnearly every working politician in\nhis state by bolting Al Smith in\n1925. Simmons had created a strong\nmachine, but it turned on him and\ndestroyed him after he had de\nserted his party. There was noi\npopular uprising against Simmons.\nNeither was the Bailey victory any\nthing in the nature of a wet vic-\ntory, as some writers have suggest\ned. The voters followed the guid\nance of their political leaders rather 1\nBurgess Bedtime Stories\nBy THORNTON W. BURGESS\nWho never knows parental cares\nIn life\u2019s great problems never shares.\n\u2014Old Mother Nature.\n\u201cThe first time I asked you how\nmany children we had. do you re\nmember what you said?\u201d asked Jerry\nMuskrat of Mrs. Muskrat.\n\"No,\u201d replied she. What did I\nsay?\u2019\u2019\n\"Plenty,\u201d replied Jerry, and\ngrinned. \u201cYou certainly told the\ntruth. We did have plenty and\nwe\u2019ve still got plenty. But how long\nwe\u2019ll have them is another ques\ntion. There goes a youngster\ncrawling right up on that bank.\nWhat chance would he have if Red\ntail the Hawk should come along?\nOr Reddy Fox should be lying low\nup there?\u201d\nMrs. Muskrat didn\u2019t stop to make\nreply. She hurried after the wan\ndering youngster and sent him back\nin a hurry. In fact, she sent him\nrolling down the bank so that he\nsplashed into the water. He was\nwhimpering, but she paid no at\ntention to him. You see, another\none was boldiy swimming out into\nthe middle of the Smiling Pool.\nMrs. Muskrat hurried after this one\nand sent him back in a hurry.\n\u201cYou might at least help to try to\nkeep these children out of danger,\u201d\nSixteen Years Ago\nS. S. Badger expects to leave\nsoon for California for a vaca\ntion and will make the trip in\nhis Cartercar.\nMr. and Mrs. David Benshi\nmol will leave Sunday for a\nvacation trip of several weeks.\nMrs. C. E. Lepine and daugh\nter will leave today for Camp\nRincon, Calif., to remain dur\ning the summer. Mr. Lepine\nwill spend some time with them\nlater.\nC. A. Carroll, assistant cash\nier of the Nacozari railway,\nleft last night for Los Angeles\nwhere he will be married to a\nformer classmate. The couple\nwill spend their honeymoon in\nEurope, returning to Douglas in\nthe fall.\nMiss Marion Roach and Dr.\nL. W. Downs will be married\ntoday in Los Angeles at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. H. A.\nStrodthoff.\nJames S. Douglas has return\ned from an inspection trip to\nthe United Verde Extension\nmine at Jerome, and reports\nthe mine showing up excel\nlently.\nD. B. Hutchins, county school\nsuperintendent, and Miss Maude\nJohnson, his deputy, were mar\nried Monday night in Tucson.\nRev. I. L. Oakes, former pas\ntor of the Methodist church\nand under whose pastorate the\nchurch was built, stopped in\nDouglas yesterday en route to\nhis home in Colton, Calif., from\nati eastern trip.\nBarbs\n\u201cLudendorff blames Charle\nmagne for the defeat of the\nkaiser in the World war.\u201d You\ndon\u2019t mean champagne, do\nyou, Ludy?\nMembers of the reichstag\nhave been ordered not to re\nmove their coats during sum\nmer sessions. During heated\ndebates it would be more to\nthe point to remind them to\nkeep their shirts on.\nBrooklyn, sometimes called\n\u201cthe bedroom of New York,\u201d\nshould be just the place to try\nout those new shorts and street\npajamas.\nThe millionaire New York\nbroker who used to give away\nSIOO tips and is now broke,\nprobably is cursing the hard\ntimes and wishing for a return\nof prosperity.\nThe boy who was told he\u2019d\nnever get anywhere unless he\nkept his hair immaculate, can\nnow point to Ambassador Mor\nrow.\nFlorida is where most pine\napples are grown. Chicago is\nwhere most are thrown.\n(Copyright, 1930, NEA Service, Inc.)\nthan that of their spiritual lead-\ners; both sets of loaders are dry.\n\nPinchot an Exception\nPuddler Jim Davis, who had all\nthe organization support, was nom\ninated by Pennsylvania republi\ncans for senator. The victory of\nGifford Pinchot in the guberna\ntorial fight, despite machine oppo\nsition, may be considered an ex\nception to the general rule that in\nbig states the organization candi\ndate always wins.\nSenator McMaster\u2019s renomination\nin South Dakota last month is\ncomparable to Senator Schall\u2019s in\nMinnesota; McMaster is an insur\ngent republican.\nRuth Hanna McCormick\u2019s defeat\nof Senator Deneen in Illinois was\nnot a victory for anything in par\nticular except the idea that most 1\nvoters aren't afraid of having a I\nwoman in the senate and the be\nlief that Deneen had never made\nhimself popular. Both Ruth and\nCharlie had their own organiza\ntions.\nIllinois has always been satu\nrated with anti-world court propa\nganda from the Chicago news\npapers. but the importance of that\nissue in determining the outcome\nprobably was considerably exagger\nated. I\nDOUGLAS ARIZONA\nPlenty!\nfife\nh\n,I^, 1\n\u2022\u2019No,\u201d replied she. \u201cWhat did I say?\u201d\nshe said crossly to Jerry.\nJerry said nothing, but started\nafter another of the youngsters, who\nwas too boldly exploring the shored\nBy the lime he had sent this one\nback, another demanded his atten\ntion. \u201cPlenty was right!\" muttered\nJerry under his breath. \u201cPlenty\ncertainly was right! I don\u2019t know\nhow we\u2019re ever going to keep all\nthese little scamps out of danger.\nThe first thing they need to learn\nis the danger signal. I must take\n;it up with Mrs. Muskrat. I cer\ntainly must take it up right away.\u201d\nSo Jerry swam over to where Mrs.\nMuskrat was. Just as soon as he got\na chance he said: \u201cMy dear, it\nseems to me very important that\nthese scamps of ours should learn\n1 the danger signal right away and\nwhat to do when they hear it. We\ncan\u2019t go running after them every\ntime they stray away, because while\nwe are chasing one, another goes.\nBut we can teach them' the hit\nand-dive signal.\u201d\n\u201cI presume you mean tail-slap\nping,\u201d said Mrs. Muskrat. \u201cI was\nthinking about that myself. You\nknow, we sometimes know things for\niso long that we forget that other\npeople don\u2019t know them. Now, I\ncan't remember when /I didn\u2019t know\nenough to dive the instant I heard\na tail slap the water. Of course,\nthese little folks of ours are not\nsuch good divers as yet, but they\nare learning. They are learning\nevery day. The first thing we know\nthey\u2019ll be grown up and leave us.\nI I\u2019ll round them up now and we\u2019ll\nI teach them what tail-slappiu A\nmeans.\u201d\nAfter some trouble Mrs. MusKWt I\nI got the nine children around her.\n1 \"Now,\u201d said she, \"it is time you\nt children learned one of the most\nimportant lessons m all the Great\nWorld.\u201d\nI \u201cWhat is that?\u201d squeaked one of\nthe little Muskrats.\n\"Obedience to the danger signal,\u201d\nreplied Mother Muskrat. \"We Musk\n>rats have one signal that we all\nknew and all heed. It is used when\none of us discovers possible danger.\nIt is a slap of a tail on the water.\nNew, your father is going to swim\nacioss the Smiling Pool. When he\ngets over there, he will pretend that\nhe has discoveied danger. You will\nhear his signal. When you hear it,\nyou do just what I do.\u201d\n1 So Jerry swan, across the Smiling\nPool. When he got across he sud\ndenly dived; and as he did so, he hit\nthe water a smart blow with His tail.\nIt made a sharp sound. Instantly,\nMother Muskrat dived; and as she\nwent under, she nli, the water with\nher tail. The nine little Muskrats\nlooked at one another uncertainly.\nThen Mother Muskrat reappeared.\n\u201cThat was the danger signal,\u201d said\nshe, \"and I showed you what to do.\nNow, we\u2019ll all try it.\u201d\nI (Copyright, 1930, T. W. Burgess)\nThe next stcry: \u201cA School of\nSaiety.\u201d\nPlucked From\nThe Plains\n\nWillie: \u201cDid Edison make the\nfirst talking machine?\u201d\nPa: \u201cNo, son, God made the\nfirst talking machine, gut Edison\nmade the first one that could be\nshut off.\u201d\nPreparin' to Sew Him in\nThe village school teacher re\nceived the following note:\nj \u201cMiss\n\u201cPlease excuse John for being\nabsent yesterday from school, be\ncause I was washing his win>r j\nunderwear and it won\u2019t happeiflA\nagain this year.\u2019\u2019\nTwo Hearts That Beat As One\nI \u201cDo you ever agree with your\nI wife?\"\n\u201cI did once, when our house was\nburning down, and we both tried\n;to get out first at the door!\u201d\u2014\n1 Nebelspalter.\n\u201cPop, what\u2019s a substitute mean?\"\n\u201cThe right article, son. made out\nof the wrong materials.\" Ex\nchange.\nBaa! Baa!\nWhat is steel wool?\nThe fleece of a hydraulic ram.\nSalesman rushing excitedly into\npolice station): I\u2019ve just killed a\npurchasing agent.\nPolice Sergeant: You\u2019ve come to\nthe wrong place. You have to go\nto the county clerk\u2019s office to col\nlect the bounty.\nMore Brains (at piano recital):\nWhat is that charming thing he is\nplaying?\nI Less Brains: A piano, y\u2019 dub.\u2014\nRoyal Arcanum Bulletin.\n#$X\nAbe Martin\nif. if. if. if. if. if. if. if.\n\u201cWell, If ther\u2019s anything in\na chin. I f^ty Roumania.\u201d said\nTell Binkley, today, speakin\u2019 o\u2019\nKing Carol 11. \u201cUse yonr\nhead. You\u2019re worsen* Jack\nSharkey,\u201d said Mrs. Tilford\nl Moots to her husban\u2019. who wim\ntry in\u2019 to ring a hog.","height":"26361","width":"20595"}}
